<p>In <a href="http://stackoverflow.com/a/29648753">Louis' answer</a>, there is the following code: </p>  <blockquote> <pre><code>describe("ModuleName", function() {     var mod;      beforeAll(function (done) {         // This loads your module and saves it in `mod`.         require(['../js/app/ModuleName'], function(mod_) {             mod = _mod;             done();         });     });      it("exists", function(){         expect(mod).toBeDefined();         expect(mod.init).toBeDefined();     }); }); </code></pre> </blockquote>  <p>They pass a function <code>done()</code> into the mix. Why do they use this? </p>